         <abstract>
            <p>This note shows the potential benefits from refunding discounted debt. These benefits are attributed to a larger tax shield deriving from the higher interest payments on the newly-issued debt. In effect, as a result of the refunding, the corporation is using larger tax deductible interest payments to replace principal repayments that are not tax deductible. Even so, such benefits may not be large enough to offset costs associated with refunding.</p>
